Continuity¶

When is a function continouous?

Geometrically, you can think of a function that is continuous at every number in an interval as a function whose graph has no break in it. The graph can be drawn without removing your pen from the paper.

Definition¶

function is continuous at a number $a$ if

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a} f(x) = f(a) \end{equation}

This deifinition requires three things:

  1. $f(a)$ is defined (that is, $a$ is in the domain of $f$). </br>

  2. $lim_{x\to a} f(x)$ exists </br>

  3. $lim_{x\to a} f(x)=f(a)$

  • A continuous function $f$ has the property that a small change in $x$ produces only a small change in $f$. </br>
  • The change in $f$ can be kept as small as we please by keeping the change in $x$ sufficiently small.

We say that $f$ is discontinuous at $a$ (or has a discontinuity at $a$) if $f$ is not continuous at $a$.

Here are some more examples of discontinuity:

A function is continuous from the right at a number $a$ if

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a^+} f(x) = f(a) \end{equation}

and is continuous from the left at $a$ if

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a^-} f(x) = f(a) \end{equation}

A function is continuous on an interval if it is continuous at every number in the interval. (If f is defined only on one side of an endpoint of the interval, we understand continuous at the endpoint to mean continuous from the right or continuous from the left.)

If $f$ and $g$ are continuous at $a$ and $c$ is a constant, then the following functions are also continuous at $a$:

  1. $f+g$ </br>

  2. $f-g$ </br>

  3. $cf$ </br>

  4. $fg$ </br>

  5. $ \Large{\frac{f}{g}}$ if $g(a)\ne 0$

Theorem¶

The following types of functions are continuous at every number in their domains:

  1. Polynomials </br>

  2. Rational functions </br>

  3. Root functions </br>

  4. Trigonometric functions </br>

  5. Inverse trigonometric functions </br>

  6. Exponential functions </br>

  7. Logarithmic functions

Theorem¶

If $g$ is continuous at $a$ and $lim_{x\to a}g(x)=b$, then $lim_{x\to a}f\big(g(x)\big)=f(b)$. In other words,

\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a} f\big(g(x)\big) = f\big(\lim_{x\to a} g(x)\big) \end{equation}

Theorem¶

If $g$ is continuous at $a$ and $f$ is continuous at $g(a)$, then the composite function $f\circ g$ given by $(f\circ g) (x)=f\big(g(x)\big)$ is continuous at $a$.

In other words: a continuous function of a continuous function is a continuous function.

THE INTERMEDIATE VALUE THEOREM¶

Suppose that $f$ is continuous on the closed interval $[a,b]$ and let $N$ be any number between $f(a)$ and $f(b)$, where $f(a)\ne f(b)$. Then there exists a number $c$ in $(a,b)$ such that $f(c)=N$.

One use of the Intermediate Value Theorem is in locating roots of equations:

Continuity in $\Re^3$¶

A function $f$ of two variables is called continuous at $(a,b)$ if

\begin{equation} \lim_{(x,y)\to (a,b)} f(x,y) =f(a,b) \end{equation}

We say $f$ is continuous on $D$ if is continuous at every point $(a,b)$ in $D$.

DIFFERENTIABILITY¶

The tangent problem¶

A tangent to a curve is a line that touches the curve.

Tangent to a circle:

Line that intersects the circle once and only once.

For more complicated curves this definition is inadequate:

Example¶

Find an equation of the tangent line to the parabola $y=x^2$ at the point P=(1,1).

  • We need the the slope of the line $m$ at (0.5,0.25).
  • We need 2 points to calculate a slope.
  • We can compute an approximation to $m$ by choosing a nerby point $Q=(x,x^2)$
\begin{equation} m_{PQ}=\frac{x^2-0.25}{x-0.5} \end{equation}
  • The line defined by the points $P$ and $Q$ is the secant line

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

def tangent(x0,x1,zoom):
    x=np.linspace(-10.2,10.2,1000)
    msec=(x1**2-x0**2)/(x1-x0)
    m=2*x0

    plt.plot(x,x**2)

    if zoom:
        plt.ylim(-0.1,2)
        plt.xlim(0,2)     
    else:
        plt.ylim(-0.1,2)
        plt.xlim(-1,2)
        
    plt.axvline(x = 0, color = 'k')
    plt.axhline(y = 0, color = 'k')
    plt.plot(x0,x0**2,'o')
    plt.annotate('$P({},{})$'.format(x0,round(x0**2,2)),xy=(x0+0.1,x0**2), color='tab:orange')
    plt.plot(x,msec*(x-x0)+x0**2, '--', color='tab:orange')
    plt.plot(x,m*(x-x0)+x0**2)

    plt.plot(x1,x1**2,'o',color='tab:orange')
    plt.annotate('$Q({},{})$'.format(x1,round(x1**2,2)),xy=(x1-0.3,x1**2+0.1), color='tab:orange')

We say that the slope of the tangent line is the limit of the slopes of the secant lines, and we express this symbolically by writing

\begin{equation} \lim_{Q\to P} m_{PQ} = m \end{equation}

Then if $P=(x_0,y_0)$,

\begin{equation} m=\lim_{x\to x_0} m_{PQ} = \lim_{x\to x_0}\frac{x^2-x^2_0}{x-x_0}=2x_0 \end{equation}

We use the point-slope form of the equation of a line to write the equation of the tangent line through as

\begin{equation} y=2x_0(x-x_0)+x^2_0 \end{equation}

Then, if we want to find the tangent line a curve $C$ that has equation $y=f(x)$ in the point $P(a,f(a))$:

  1. We compute the slope of the secant line defined by the points $P$ and $q(x,f(x))$, taking $x\ne a$:
\begin{equation} m_{sec}=\frac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a} \end{equation}
  1. We let $Q$ approach $P$ along the curve by letting $x$ approach $a$.
\begin{equation} m=\lim_{x\to a}\frac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a} \end{equation}

Definition¶

The tangent line to the curve $y=f(x)$ at the point $P(a,f(a))$ is the line through $P$ with slope

\begin{equation} m=\lim_{x\to a}\frac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a} \end{equation}

provided that this limit exists.

Equivalently, if $\Delta x=x-a$ then $x=a+\Delta x$

\begin{equation} m=\lim_{\Delta x\to 0}\frac{f(a+\Delta x)-f(a)}{\Delta x} \end{equation}

Definition¶

The derivative of a function $f$ at a number $a$, denoted by $f'(a)$, is

\begin{equation} f'(a)=\lim_{\Delta x\to 0}\frac{f(a+\Delta x)-f(a)}{\Delta x} \end{equation}

if this limit exists.

Equivalently,

\begin{equation} f'(a)=\lim_{x\to a}\frac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a} \end{equation}

Definition¶

A function is differentiable at $a$ if $f'(a)$ exists. It is differentiable on an open interval $(a,b)$ (or $(a,\infty)$ or $(-\infty,a)$ or $(-\infty,\infty)$) if it is differentiable at every number in the interval.

Definition¶

The tangent line to $y=f(x)$ at the point $(a,f(a))$ is the line through $(a,f(a))$ whose slope is equal to $f'(a)$, the derivative of $f$ at $a$.

Rates of change¶

Suppose $y$ is a function of $x$, $y=f(x)$. if $x$ changes from $x_1$ to $x_2$, then the change in x is

\begin{equation} \Delta x=x_2-x_1 \end{equation}

The corresponding change in $y$ is:

\begin{equation} \Delta y=f(x_2)-f(x_1) \end{equation}

The difference quotient

\begin{equation} \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{f(x_2)-f(x_1)}{x_2-x_1} \end{equation}

is called the average rate of change of $y$ with respect to $x$ over the interval $[x_1,x_2]$ and can be interpreted as the slope of the secant line $PQ$.

The instantaneous rate of change is

\begin{equation} \lim_{\Delta x\to 0}\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\lim_{x_2\to x_1}\frac{f(x_2)-f(x_1)}{x_2-x_1}=f'(x_1) \end{equation}

For example, the average velocity is the average rate of change of the position $x$ respect to the time $t$, that is, the variation of the position in a certain time interval.

\begin{equation} v_{AV}=\frac{x-x_0}{t-t_0}=\frac{\Delta x}{\Delta t} \end{equation}

Where $x$ is a function of the time: $x=x(t)$.

The instantaneous velocity is the velocy at a certain time and it is calculated by taking a "very small" time interval:

\begin{equation} v=\lim_{t \to t_0}\frac{x(t)-x(t_0)}{t-t_0}\lim_{\Delta t \to 0}\frac{\Delta x}{\Delta t}=x'(t) \end{equation}

This means that the velocity at time $t_0$ is equal to the slope of the tangent line at $P(t_0,x_0)$ and it is the derivative of the position respect to the time at $t_0$

  • If $s=f(t)$ is the position function of a particle that moves along a straight line, then $f'(t_0)$ is the rate of change of the displacement $s$ with respect to the time at $t_0$.

  • In other words, $f'(t_0)$ is the velocity of the particle at $t_0$.

  • $|f'(t_0)|$ is the speed.

  • When the derivative is large, the curve is steep and the values of $y$ change rapidly.

Another notation for the derivative:

\begin{equation} f'(a)=\lim_{\Delta x\to 0}\frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{d y}{d x}\big|_{x=a} \end{equation}

THE DERIVATIVE AS A FUNCTION¶

If we calculate the derivative at an arbitrary point $x$, we can define a new function:

\begin{equation} f'(x)=\lim_{\Delta x\to 0}\frac{f(x+\Delta x)-f(x)}{\Delta x} \end{equation}

$f'(x)$ is the derivative of $f$

The derivative of the addition/substraction¶

\begin{equation} \big(f+g\big)'(x)=~? \end{equation}
\begin{equation} \big(f+g\big)'(x)=\lim_{\Delta x \to 0}\frac{\big(f+g\big)(x+\Delta x)-\big(f+g\big)(x)}{\Delta x}= \end{equation}
\begin{equation} =\lim_{\Delta x \to 0}\frac{f(x+\Delta x)+g(x+\Delta x)-f(x)-g(x)}{\Delta x} \end{equation}
\begin{equation} =\lim_{\Delta x \to 0}\frac{f(x+\Delta x)-f(x)}{\Delta x}+\lim_{\Delta x \to 0}\frac{g(x+\Delta x)-g(x)}{\Delta x}=f'(x)+g'(x) \end{equation}

The derivative of the product¶

\begin{equation} \big(f\cdot g\big)'(x)=~? \end{equation}
\begin{equation} =\lim_{\Delta x \to 0}\frac{f(x+\Delta x)\cdot g(x+\Delta x)-f(x)\cdot g(x)}{\Delta x} \end{equation}

if

\begin{equation} f(x+\Delta x)=f(x)+\Delta f \end{equation}\begin{equation} g(x+\Delta x)=g(x)+\Delta g \end{equation}
\begin{equation} \big(f\cdot g\big)'(x)=\lim_{\Delta x \to 0}\frac{\big(f(x)+\Delta f\big)\cdot \big(g(x)+\Delta g\big)-f(x)\cdot g(x)}{\Delta x} \end{equation}
\begin{equation} \big(f\cdot g\big)'(x)=\lim_{\Delta x \to 0}\frac{f(x) \cdot g(x) +\Delta f \cdot g(x) +f(x) \Delta g +\Delta f \Delta g -f(x)\cdot g(x)}{\Delta x}= \end{equation}
\begin{equation} \big(f\cdot g\big)'(x)=\lim_{\Delta x \to 0}\frac{\Delta f \cdot g(x) +f(x) \Delta g +\Delta f \Delta g }{\Delta x}= \end{equation}
\begin{equation} \big(f\cdot g\big)'(x)=\lim_{\Delta x \to 0}\bigg(\frac{\Delta f}{\Delta x}\cdot g(x)+f(x) \frac{\Delta g}{\Delta x}+\frac{\Delta f \Delta g}{\Delta x}\bigg)= \end{equation}
\begin{equation} \big(f\cdot g\big)'(x)=\lim_{\Delta x \to 0}\bigg(\frac{\Delta f}{\Delta x}\cdot g(x)+f(x) \frac{\Delta g}{\Delta x}+\frac{\Delta f \Delta g \Delta x}{\Delta x \Delta x}\bigg)=f(x)\cdot g'(x)+g(x)\cdot f'(x) \end{equation}

since \begin{equation} \lim_{\Delta x \to 0}\frac{\Delta f \Delta g \Delta x}{\Delta x \Delta x}=f'(x)\cdot g'(x) \cdot 0=0 \end{equation}

The derivative of the division¶

Similarly...

\begin{equation} \big(f \big / g\big)'(x)=...=\frac{f'(x)\cdot g(x)-g'(x)\cdot f(x)}{g^2(x)},~~~ g(x)\ne 0 \end{equation}

You can consider that $f(x) \big / g(x)=f(x)\cdot \big(1\big/ g(x)\big)$ and apply the derivative of the product.

Relation between continuity and differentiability¶

Theorem¶

if $f(x)$ is differentiable, then $f(x)$ is continuous.

differentiability $\Rightarrow$ continuity but the oposite is not true.

The study of differentiability¶

HOW CAN A FUNCTION FAIL TO BE DIFFERENTIABLE?¶

  • If the graph of a function has a corner or kink in it, then the graph of has no tangent at this point and is not differentiable there.
  • if $f$ is not continuous at $a$, then $f$ is not differentiable at $a$.
  • A third possibility is that the curve has a vertical tangent line when $x=a$; that is, $f$ is continuous at $a$ and
\begin{equation} \lim_{x\to a}f'(x)=\infty \end{equation}

Theorem¶

f(x) is differentiable if f(x) is continuous

Diferentiation Rules Summary¶

DERIVATIVE OF A CONSTANT FUNCTION

\begin{equation} \frac{d}{dx}\big(c\big)=0 \end{equation}

THE POWER RULE

\begin{equation} \frac{d}{dx}\big[x^n\big]=nx^{n-1},~~~ n~ is~ any~ real~ number \end{equation}

THE CONSTANT MULTIPLE RULE

\begin{equation} \frac{d}{dx}\big[cf(x)\big]=c \frac{d}{dx}f(x) \end{equation}

THE SUM RULE

\begin{equation} \frac{d}{dx}\big[f(x)+g(x)\big]= \frac{d}{dx}f(x)+\frac{d}{dx}g(x) \end{equation}

THE DIFFERENCE RULE

\begin{equation} \frac{d}{dx}\big[f(x)-g(x)\big]= \frac{d}{dx}f(x)-\frac{d}{dx}g(x) \end{equation}

THE PRODUCT RULE

\begin{equation} \frac{d}{dx}\big[f(x)\cdot g(x)\big]= \frac{d}{dx}f(x)\cdot g(x)+f(x)\cdot \frac{d}{dx}g(x) \end{equation}

THE QUOTIENT RULE

\begin{equation} \frac{d}{dx}\bigg[\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\bigg]= \frac{\frac{d}{dx}f(x)\cdot g(x)-f(x)\cdot \frac{d}{dx}g(x)}{\big[g(x)\big]^2} \end{equation}

DERIVATIVE OF THE NATURAL EXPONENTIAL FUNCTION

\begin{equation} \frac{d}{dx}\big(e^x\big)= e^x \end{equation}

DERIVATIVE OF THE NATURAL LOGARITHM

\begin{equation} \frac{d}{dx}\big[\ln(x)\big]= \frac{1}{x},~~~ x >0 \end{equation}
